{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-post-js","path":"/blog/working-on-a-bigcommerce-custom-checkout-locally/","result":{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"Jack Harner","description":"Jack Harner is a Freelance Web Developer & E-Commerce Consultant based in Denver, Colorado. Shopify, BigCommerce, WordPress Dev & More.","author":"@jackharner","siteUrl":"https://jackharner.com"}},"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>When building or modifying BigCommerce's Open Source checkout-js, the only way <a href=\"https://developer.bigcommerce.com/docs/storefront/cart-checkout/open-checkouts/guide\">the docs claim</a> you can access the locally running version of your custom checkout is by changing the Checkout Script URL setting directly on the site settings. This breaks that store's checkout for anyone except the developer. BigCommerce obviously recommends only working on a custom checkout on a staging store, but that doesn't always work. It's nice to be able to work with live data while testing and developing the checkout locally.</p>\n<p>Modifying the Open Source checkout for a BigCommerce store is no simple task (it's a highly sophisticated React application). Doing so for a production site without completely nuking the live site's actual checkout seemed impossible. Thanks to the BigCommerceDevs Slack (see credits section at the end), it turns out it is actually possible!</p>\n<p>Let's jump into how:</p>\n<div class=\"table-of-contents\">\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#stencil-cli-meets-open-source-checkout\">Stencil-CLI Meets Open Source Checkout</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#a-few-simple-modifications-to-the-checkouthtml\">A Few Simple Modifications To The Checkout.html</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#now-youre-working-on-the-bc-checkout-locally\">Now You're Working On The BC Checkout Locally</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#credits\">Credits</a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<h2 id=\"stencil-cli-meets-open-source-checkout\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#stencil-cli-meets-open-source-checkout\" aria-label=\"stencil cli meets open source checkout permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Stencil-CLI Meets Open Source Checkout</h2>\n<p>If you're working with BigCommerce's open source <a href=\"https://github.com/bigcommerce/checkout-js\">checkout-js</a> (or the <a href=\"https://github.com/bigcommerce/checkout-sdk-js\">checkout-sdk</a>, though the steps may be slightly different, I'm not sure), I probably don't need to tell you this, but to work on your custom checkout locally you need:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>A Stencil theme set up to work locally with the stencil-cli</li>\n<li>BC's Open Source Checkout forked and cloned locally</li>\n<li><code class=\"language-text\">stencil start</code> running in the theme's terminal</li>\n<li><code class=\"language-text\">npm run dev &amp; npm run dev:server</code> running separately in the checkout's terminal</li>\n</ol>\n<p>I'm going to assume you're using these tool's default urls/ports (at the time of writing) but if you for some reason are using something else, just make sure to substitute my values with your own.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"text\"><pre class=\"language-text\"><code class=\"language-text\">Theme Running on: http://localhost:3000\nCheckout running on: http://127.0.0.1:8080</code></pre></div>\n<h2 id=\"a-few-simple-modifications-to-the-checkouthtml\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#a-few-simple-modifications-to-the-checkouthtml\" aria-label=\"a few simple modifications to the checkouthtml permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>A Few Simple Modifications To The Checkout.html</h2>\n<p>Inside your theme's checkout page template, <code class=\"language-text\">/templates/pages/checkout.html</code> we need to make a few changes: modifying the checkout content based on the environment we're running the theme and adding some configuration settings to the window to overwrite where it looks for checkout scripts.</p>\n<p>Find your theme's <code class=\"language-text\">{{{ checkout.checkout_content }}}</code> and wrap it in an if/else checking the <code class=\"language-text\">in_production</code> variable. The else gets an empty div with a <code class=\"language-text\">checkout-app</code> id:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"handlebars\"><pre class=\"language-handlebars\"><code class=\"language-handlebars\"><span class=\"token handlebars language-handlebars\"><span class=\"token delimiter punctuation\">{{</span><span class=\"token block keyword\">#if</span> <span class=\"token variable\">in_production</span><span class=\"token delimiter punctuation\">}}</span></span>\n  <span class=\"token handlebars language-handlebars\"><span class=\"token delimiter punctuation\">{{{</span> <span class=\"token variable\">checkout</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token variable\">checkout_content</span> <span class=\"token delimiter punctuation\">}}}</span></span>\n<span class=\"token handlebars language-handlebars\"><span class=\"token delimiter punctuation\">{{</span><span class=\"token variable\">else</span><span class=\"token delimiter punctuation\">}}</span></span>\n  <span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;</span>div</span> <span class=\"token attr-name\">id</span><span class=\"token attr-value\"><span class=\"token punctuation attr-equals\">=</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">\"</span>checkout-app<span class=\"token punctuation\">\"</span></span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;/</span>div</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span>\n<span class=\"token handlebars language-handlebars\"><span class=\"token delimiter punctuation\">{{</span><span class=\"token block keyword\">/if</span><span class=\"token delimiter punctuation\">}}</span></span></code></pre></div>\n<p>Just above the <code class=\"language-text\">{{{ footer.scripts }}}</code> tag add the following if statement triggering only if you're using the stencil-cli to run the theme (the <code class=\"language-text\">in_development</code> variable):</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"handlebars\"><pre class=\"language-handlebars\"><code class=\"language-handlebars\"><span class=\"token handlebars language-handlebars\"><span class=\"token delimiter punctuation\">{{</span><span class=\"token block keyword\">#if</span> <span class=\"token variable\">in_development</span><span class=\"token delimiter punctuation\">}}</span></span>\n  <span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;</span>script</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span><span class=\"token script\"><span class=\"token language-javascript\">\n    window<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>checkoutConfig <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span> \n        <span class=\"token literal-property property\">containerId</span><span class=\"token operator\">:</span> <span class=\"token string\">\"checkout-app\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span>\n        <span class=\"token literal-property property\">checkoutId</span><span class=\"token operator\">:</span> <span class=\"token string\">\"<span class=\"token handlebars language-handlebars\"><span class=\"token delimiter punctuation\">{{</span><span class=\"token variable\">cart_id</span><span class=\"token delimiter punctuation\">}}</span></span>\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span>\n        <span class=\"token literal-property property\">publicPath</span><span class=\"token operator\">:</span> <span class=\"token string\">\"http://127.0.0.1:8080/\"</span>\n    <span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n  </span></span><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;/</span>script</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span>\n  <span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;</span>script</span> <span class=\"token attr-name\">src</span><span class=\"token attr-value\"><span class=\"token punctuation attr-equals\">=</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">\"</span>http://127.0.0.1:8080/auto-loader-dev.js<span class=\"token punctuation\">\"</span></span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span><span class=\"token script\"></span><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;/</span>script</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span>\n<span class=\"token handlebars language-handlebars\"><span class=\"token delimiter punctuation\">{{</span><span class=\"token block keyword\">/if</span><span class=\"token delimiter punctuation\">}}</span></span></code></pre></div>\n<p>This tells the rest of the checkout to look for and fetch the locally hosted files output through the checkout's <code class=\"language-text\">npm run dev:server</code> command.</p>\n<h2 id=\"now-youre-working-on-the-bc-checkout-locally\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#now-youre-working-on-the-bc-checkout-locally\" aria-label=\"now youre working on the bc checkout locally permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Now You're Working On The BC Checkout Locally</h2>\n<p>Now, whenever you're running your theme locally through Stencil CLI, your Stencil CLI theme will utilize the locally running version of your checkout as opposed to the live one.</p>\n<p>Wrapping everything in the <code class=\"language-text\">is_development</code> &#x26; <code class=\"language-text\">is_production</code> variables allows for some peace of mind at the fact that you'll never leave the checkout completely dead in the water.</p>\n<p>This does mean that anytime you need to test anything in the checkout or order-confirmation locally, you <em>have</em> to have the custom checkout repo cloned locally and running alongside stencil-cli. If you're working on a store that needs a custom checkout you can bundle both packages into the same repo to make that a little easier to manage.</p>\n<p>This little hiccup in the development process is vastly outweighed by the benefit of being able to take advantage of the stencil-cli connected to a live production site, working locally, <em>and</em> working on a custom checkout without breaking production.</p>\n<h2 id=\"credits\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#credits\" aria-label=\"credits permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Credits</h2>\n<p>Credit for the discovery goes to <a href=\"https://www.linkedin.com/in/andrewabarber\">Andrew A. Barber</a>, the Engineering Manager @ <a href=\"https://www.space48.com/\">Space 48</a>, whom I met on the <a href=\"https://developer.bigcommerce.com/docs/start/about/support#developer-slack\">BigCommerce Devs Slack group</a>. If you're a BigCommerce Developer, and <em>NOT</em> in that slack group, I highly recommend you join. It's a great place to ask hyper-specific questions and get some answers from the top minds in the space.</p>\n<p>Also huge shoutout to my <a href=\"/services/ghost-coding/\">ghost-coding-client-who-shall-not-be-named</a> for trusting me to dig into the BigCommerce Open Source Checkout for the first time and paying me to learn on the clock.</p>","excerpt":"When building or modifying BigCommerce's Open Source checkout-js, the only way the docs claim you can access the locally running version of your…","wordCount":{"words":610},"frontmatter":{"date":"January 21, 2024","updated":null,"title":"Working On A BigCommerce Custom Checkout Locally","subtitle":"Without Breaking Your Store's Live Checkout","tags":["BigCommerce","React"],"featuredImage":{"absolutePath":"/home/runner/work/jackharner-gatsby/jackharner-gatsby/content/blog/working-on-a-bigcommerce-custom-checkout-locally/ramiro-mendes-sMCBEI5zkqc-unsplash.jpg","childImageSharp":{"gatsbyImageData":{"layout":"fullWidth","backgroundColor":"#181828","images":{"fallback":{"src":"/static/2baa625f612c08834e3070aa5d45db72/a7828/ramiro-mendes-sMCBEI5zkqc-unsplash.jpg","srcSet":"/static/2baa625f612c08834e3070aa5d45db72/05435/ramiro-mendes-sMCBEI5zkqc-unsplash.jpg 750w,\n/static/2baa625f612c08834e3070aa5d45db72/81c74/ramiro-mendes-sMCBEI5zkqc-unsplash.jpg 1080w,\n/static/2baa625f612c08834e3070aa5d45db72/b2594/ramiro-mendes-sMCBEI5zkqc-unsplash.jpg 1366w,\n/static/2baa625f612c08834e3070aa5d45db72/a7828/ramiro-mendes-sMCBEI5zkqc-unsplash.jpg 1920w","sizes":"100vw"},"sources":[{"srcSet":"/static/2baa625f612c08834e3070aa5d45db72/15f20/ramiro-mendes-sMCBEI5zkqc-unsplash.webp 750w,\n/static/2baa625f612c08834e3070aa5d45db72/9a568/ramiro-mendes-sMCBEI5zkqc-unsplash.webp 1080w,\n/static/2baa625f612c08834e3070aa5d45db72/e2fc4/ramiro-mendes-sMCBEI5zkqc-unsplash.webp 1366w,\n/static/2baa625f612c08834e3070aa5d45db72/9333a/ramiro-mendes-sMCBEI5zkqc-unsplash.webp 1920w","type":"image/webp","sizes":"100vw"}]},"width":1,"height":0.6692708333333334}}},"ogImage":{"absolutePath":"/home/runner/work/jackharner-gatsby/jackharner-gatsby/content/blog/working-on-a-bigcommerce-custom-checkout-locally/working-on-a-bigcommerce-custom-checkout-og-image.png","childImageSharp":{"gatsbyImageData":{"layout":"constrained","backgroundColor":"#f8f8f8","images":{"fallback":{"src":"/static/1a012b0b969e9ce7aa96de4ca7f5665e/b5380/working-on-a-bigcommerce-custom-checkout-og-image.png","srcSet":"/static/1a012b0b969e9ce7aa96de4ca7f5665e/a0e1b/working-on-a-bigcommerce-custom-checkout-og-image.png 300w,\n/static/1a012b0b969e9ce7aa96de4ca7f5665e/86184/working-on-a-bigcommerce-custom-checkout-og-image.png 600w,\n/static/1a012b0b969e9ce7aa96de4ca7f5665e/b5380/working-on-a-bigcommerce-custom-checkout-og-image.png 1200w,\n/static/1a012b0b969e9ce7aa96de4ca7f5665e/6b063/working-on-a-bigcommerce-custom-checkout-og-image.png 2400w","sizes":"(min-width: 1200px) 1200px, 100vw"},"sources":[{"srcSet":"/static/1a012b0b969e9ce7aa96de4ca7f5665e/c7da1/working-on-a-bigcommerce-custom-checkout-og-image.webp 300w,\n/static/1a012b0b969e9ce7aa96de4ca7f5665e/22c65/working-on-a-bigcommerce-custom-checkout-og-image.webp 600w,\n/static/1a012b0b969e9ce7aa96de4ca7f5665e/81547/working-on-a-bigcommerce-custom-checkout-og-image.webp 1200w,\n/static/1a012b0b969e9ce7aa96de4ca7f5665e/19ade/working-on-a-bigcommerce-custom-checkout-og-image.webp 2400w","type":"image/webp","sizes":"(min-width: 1200px) 1200px, 100vw"}]},"width":1200,"height":630}}}},"fields":{"externalLink":"","externalLinkLabel":"Check It Out »","slug":"/blog/working-on-a-bigcommerce-custom-checkout-locally/","ogImage":"./working-on-a-bigcommerce-custom-checkout-og-image.png","date":"January 21, 2024","unlisted":false}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/blog/working-on-a-bigcommerce-custom-checkout-locally/","related":[{"id":"46dde03b-71ea-58ae-9a77-94d48debc139","excerpt":"Read My Diary 😉 I was asked to guest post on the BigCommerce Developer blog as part of their Developer Diaries series. The series looks at…","fields":{"date":"2019-11-22T17:14:33.962Z","slug":"/blog/bigcommerce-developer-diary/","collection":"blog","published":true,"externalLink":"https://medium.com/bigcommerce-developer-blog/developer-diary-jack-harner-shoolu-com-ad163caeda35","externalLinkLabel":"Check It Out »"},"frontmatter":{"title":"BigCommerce Developer Diary","subtitle":"A Week In My Work Life","tags":["BigCommerce","Career","Automation","E-Commerce"],"published":true,"featuredImage":{"childImageSharp":{"gatsbyImageData":{"layout":"constrained","backgroundColor":"#281878","images":{"fallback":{"src":"/static/88b5fd923814a1f1eff643a19a6cc19d/acf5a/featuredImage.png","srcSet":"/static/88b5fd923814a1f1eff643a19a6cc19d/42c0e/featuredImage.png 146w,\n/static/88b5fd923814a1f1eff643a19a6cc19d/e4066/featuredImage.png 292w,\n/static/88b5fd923814a1f1eff643a19a6cc19d/acf5a/featuredImage.png 584w,\n/static/88b5fd923814a1f1eff643a19a6cc19d/a7dae/featuredImage.png 1168w","sizes":"(min-width: 584px) 584px, 100vw"},"sources":[{"srcSet":"/static/88b5f